# Start Simple, Agile Sprints

## Mindset

- **Start simple:** Smallest viable scope first. One vertical slice (e.g. one flow end-to-end) before adding more. Avoid big upfront design.
- **Agile sprints:** Work in short, time-boxed sprints (e.g. 1–2 weeks). Each sprint delivers something demonstrable and shippable.
- **Checklist-driven:** When starting a new project or sprint, use the project checklist so nothing is skipped.

## When Starting a Project

- Prefer **minimal scope** for Sprint 0 / first sprint: one user journey, one API surface, one deploy path.
- Ensure **docs and checklist** exist: `docs/PROJECT_CHECKLIST.md` (or project-specific copy). Use it for kickoff and sprint planning.
- Don’t add features “while we’re here”; capture them in a backlog and schedule in a later sprint.

## When Planning a Sprint

- Define a **sprint goal** and a **short list of committed items** (backlog items / tasks).
- Ensure each item has a **definition of done** (see checklist).
- Prefer **small, completable tasks** over large “in progress” blocks.

## When Implementing

- Deliver **one slice at a time** (e.g. one endpoint + one screen + tests) so the product is always in a working state.
- Update **docs and checklist** when you complete setup steps or change how the project runs (e.g. how to run tests, deploy).

## Project Checklist Location

- **Checklist:** `docs/PROJECT_CHECKLIST.md` — use for new project setup, Sprint 0, and ongoing sprint cadence.
- If the user asks to “set up a checklist” or “start a project with agile,” create or update that file and follow it.
